Local engagement as a countermeasure against populism.
PARIS – Parties that once dominated Western democracies were shaken to their core.
Many – including those in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing election defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name has remained.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments resemble themselves everywhere in the West.
The former dominant parties' leaderships oscillate between denial and desperation, as populists are fishing up their traditional followers.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters as "pitiful" like Hillary Clinton did, just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are intimidated by the populist tide to the point of being too frightened to launch a counterattack.
Neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the entrenched political situation.
The Progressives must reposition themselves, and this starts with a diagnosis of the inadequacies of the traditional parties.
A major part of the problem lies in the fact that the traditional parties have not recognized the true issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlegrounds, they ignored the declining social mobility, the worsening environmental crises, the increasing geographical inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that are genuinely of concern to voters.
Years ago, they were the avant-garde.
They're all alone in the woods today, wondering where everyone is.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The chasm between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing gap in income and other statistics between some affluent, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
However, until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did it, no national government leader had implemented tax cuts based on residency in place.
As a result of this policy, 1% of French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to the voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What voters told the questioners then became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had gathered countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual harassment of women, and Macron promised to deal with the problem if he were elected.
Back then, Macron's stance made him the target of his opponents' jokes; however, this laughter soon ceased with the emergence of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
Traditional parties also suffer from poor organisation.
They had long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections where activists hand out flyers at intervals and campaign for the candidates.
That was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state suppliers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, it is the sole purpose of a party to conquer and maintain power.
It's no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years they had a technological lead over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to the elections, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer fits.
Citizens are refusing today to be mere consumers of state policy.
With a higher level of education came new demands for participation.
Voters want to be treated as political actors in their own right, not as pawns in the game of others.
In addition, governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the harsh lessons we had to learn in the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most pressing political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – cannot be solved by national governments alone.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to entry for political participation, enabling traditional parties no longer to rely on the incumbent bonus and consolidated support networks.
Those who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well, don't need a century-old party apparatus.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on the elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed with people on the ground.
We refer to these as local citizen projects at La République En Marche!
These can range from reading courses after school and integration programs for immigrants, down to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it's about offering solutions tailored to local problems and thereby strengthening the communities.
Such projects should be regarded as indispensable supplements to governmental policy today.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding pathways for political and communal engagement will be crucial to its appeal.
And by presenting their reform policies "live" every day, the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what you have to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving the lives of people, rather than simply winning elections, can win the people over.
Restoring the connection to the concerns of voters thus goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive local politics.
